The News: -- "Deeply disturbed" by India's nuclear tests, U.S. President
Bill Clinton said Tuesday he would fully implement U.S. laws that virtually
dictate sanctions as a penalty for testing and recalled the ambassador to
India for consultations. The Nation: -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Tuesday that his country alone will decide as to what is
essential to safeguard its security in the wake of Indian nuclear
explosions and will not take dictation from anybody. The Frontier Post: --
Russia warned the United States Tuesday that slapping sanctions on India
for conducting underground nuclear explosions could prove
counterproductive, however reprehensible the atomic tests were. The Muslim:
-- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said Tuesday that the latest
Indian nuclear tests have shattered the global non-proliferation regime.
